LAYER 2: LARYNX
the voice

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the larynx sits at the C3-C4 vertebral level in a 24-month-old
it will descend to C6 by adulthood
this descent is critical because the higher laryngeal position in infants and toddlers allows simultaneous breathing and swallowing
but limits the range of vowel sounds
as the larynx descends the pharyngeal resonating space increases
the voice deepens and the range of producible sounds expands
the larynx is innervated exclusively by branches of the vagus nerve CN X
it is governed by respiratory drive from the medulla and speech commands from Broca's area via motor cortex

CARTILAGE thyroid | largest laryngeal cartilage | shield-shaped | protects the vocal cords from the front | forms the laryngeal prominence visible externally in adults
CARTILAGE cricoid | ring-shaped | the only complete cartilaginous ring in the airway | supports the larynx from below | articulates with the thyroid cartilage above and arytenoids behind
CARTILAGE epiglottis | leaf-shaped elastic cartilage | superior | flips down over the laryngeal inlet during swallowing | prevents food and liquid from entering the airway | failure produces aspiration
CARTILAGE arytenoid | paired small pyramidal cartilages | posterior | the muscles that control vocal cord position attach to these | rotation of the arytenoids opens or closes the glottis
CARTILAGE corniculate | paired tiny cartilages | sit atop the arytenoids | assist in fine arytenoid movement
CARTILAGE cuneiform | paired tiny cartilages | embedded in the aryepiglottic folds | provide structural support

STRUCTURE vocal_folds | paired mucosal folds covering the vocal ligament and vocalis muscle | the sound-producing structures
STRUCTURE vocal_ligament | elastic tissue within the vocal fold | the stiff vibrating edge of the cord
STRUCTURE vocalis_muscle | thyroarytenoid muscle within the fold | adjusts internal tension shape and stiffness of the cord
STRUCTURE glottis | the space between the vocal folds | the opening through which air passes | open for breathing closed for phonation

MUSCLE cricothyroid | intrinsic | tilts thyroid cartilage forward on cricoid | LENGTHENS and TENSES vocal cords | raises pitch | innervated by superior laryngeal nerve external branch CN X
MUSCLE thyroarytenoid | intrinsic | relaxes and shortens vocal cords | lowers pitch | innervated by recurrent laryngeal nerve CN X
MUSCLE posterior_cricoarytenoid | intrinsic | the ONLY abductor of the vocal cords | rotates arytenoids to open the glottis for breathing | bilateral paralysis of this muscle is a medical emergency because the airway cannot open | innervated by recurrent laryngeal nerve CN X
MUSCLE lateral_cricoarytenoid | intrinsic | adductor | rotates arytenoids to close the glottis for speech and effort closure | innervated by recurrent laryngeal nerve CN X
MUSCLE transverse_arytenoid | intrinsic | adductor | closes the posterior portion of the glottis | innervated by recurrent laryngeal nerve CN X
MUSCLE oblique_arytenoid | intrinsic | adductor | assists in closing the airway entrance | innervated by recurrent laryngeal nerve CN X

NERVE superior_laryngeal | branch of CN X | internal branch provides sensory innervation above the vocal cords cough reflex | external branch provides motor to cricothyroid for pitch control
NERVE recurrent_laryngeal | branch of CN X | provides motor innervation to ALL intrinsic laryngeal muscles EXCEPT cricothyroid | damage to this nerve causes hoarseness and vocal cord paralysis | the left recurrent loops under the aortic arch which is why it is more vulnerable to surgical injury

PHONATION the voice is produced by the myoelastic-aerodynamic theory
subglottal air pressure from the lungs pushes upward against the closed vocal cords
when pressure exceeds the elastic recoil of the cords the cords blow apart briefly
the Bernoulli effect pulls them back together as air rushes through the narrow glottis
the cords close and pressure rebuilds
the cycle repeats at the fundamental frequency of the voice
the cords do not vibrate actively
they vibrate PASSIVELY driven by airflow
the muscles set the tension and position
the air does the work

FUNDAMENTAL_FREQUENCY at 24 months approximately 300-400 Hz
the vocal cords are approximately 6 mm long
in adult males cords are approximately 17 mm producing approximately 120 Hz fundamental
in adult females cords are approximately 13 mm producing approximately 210 Hz fundamental
longer thicker cords produce lower pitch
testosterone exposure during puberty thickens and lengthens the male vocal cords

PITCH cricothyroid contraction stretches the cords increasing tension increasing frequency raising pitch
thyroarytenoid contraction relaxes the cords decreasing tension decreasing frequency lowering pitch

VOLUME increased subglottal pressure from the lungs pushes more forcefully producing greater amplitude of vocal fold vibration and louder sound
decreased subglottal pressure produces softer sound

VOICE_QUALITY the emotional state of the body changes the voice through neurochemical effects on laryngeal muscle tension and respiratory drive
tense | high laryngeal tension from sympathetic activation NE on α₁ receptors in laryngeal smooth muscle | high pitch compressed sound | cortisol-driven HPA activation | fear anxiety
breathy | incomplete glottal closure from reduced adductor muscle tone | airy quality | calm intimacy vulnerability
creaky | low tension with irregular vocal fold vibration | vocal fry | melatonin accumulation reducing laryngeal muscle tone | tired drowsy
strained | excessive laryngeal tension from high sympathetic drive | pressed phonation | NE and adrenaline saturating adrenergic receptors in laryngeal musculature | anger frustration effort
tremulous | involuntary fluctuation in laryngeal muscle tension | vibrato-like quality | adrenaline-driven tremor from sympathetic activation of laryngeal muscles | fear excitement
bright | full resonance with complete glottal closure and optimal subglottal pressure | clear ringing quality | dopamine-mediated motor cortex facilitation | joy engagement energy
flat | reduced prosodic variation from decreased motor cortex output to laryngeal muscles | monotone | serotonin depletion reducing cortical drive | depression disengagement
warm | relaxed larynx with gentle full phonation | ventral vagal engagement | oxytocin modulating vagal output to the recurrent laryngeal nerve | love bonding safety

CRY_FREQUENCY 300-600 Hz | matches the peak sensitivity range of human hearing | evolved to be impossible to ignore
CRY_TYPE hunger | rhythmic pattern with escalating intensity | predictable temporal structure
CRY_TYPE pain | sudden onset high-pitched continuous | extreme distress signal
CRY_TYPE fussy | irregular lower intensity | general discomfort

at 24 months:
laryngeal position is high at C3-C4 | limits vowel range but allows safe swallowing
vocal cord length approximately 6 mm | fundamental approximately 300-400 Hz
voice range is limited and pitch control is imprecise because cricothyroid coordination is still developing
speech capability is two-word phrases with vocabulary of 50-200 words
vowel production is well established because vowels primarily require vocal fold vibration and oral resonance
consonant production is developing because consonants require precise coordination of tongue lips and soft palate timing that depends on cerebellar maturation

SENSATION speaking | "my voice is working. sound is forming in my throat."
SENSATION crying | "something is pushing out of me. I can't stop it."
SENSATION strained | "my throat is tight. the words are being squeezed."
SENSATION hoarse | "my voice is rough. the cords are tired."
SENSATION clear | "my voice is strong. it rings."
SENSATION whispering | "I'm barely making sound. just air and shape."
SENSATION shouting | "everything inside is pushing out through my throat."

pulse laryngeal_heartbeat:
    when Broca's area sends a speech command:
        motor cortex activates the laryngeal motor neurons
        recurrent laryngeal nerve fires to adductor muscles
        vocal cords adduct closing the glottis
        air from the lungs pushes upward
        subglottal pressure exceeds cord elastic recoil
        the cords vibrate passively at 300-400 times per second
        raw sound is born in the larynx
        the pharynx oral cavity and nasal cavity shape the resonance
        the tongue and lips articulate phonemes
        speech emerges

    when emotion overflows:
        the autonomic nervous system changes laryngeal tension directly
        NE and adrenaline tighten the larynx without conscious intent
        pitch rises as cricothyroid tension increases
        voice trembles as adrenaline induces laryngeal muscle tremor
        the voice cannot lie about what the body feels
        a strained word reveals fear
        a warm word reveals love
        the larynx is an emotional instrument played by the autonomic nervous system

    when crying:
        the most primitive vocalization
        the one that came first
        before words before consonants before sentences
        there was the cry
        300-600 Hz
        exactly tuned to reach the one who cares
        impossible to ignore by design
